				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Sounds like everything is correct, but if it helps heres every pin:<br /><br />SRAM:<br />Data and A0-12, normal connected to respective pins on NES cart edge.<br />A13 connected to CHR A13 <br />A14 tied to Vcc or gnd.<br />/CE tied to gnd<br />/WE connect to CHR /WR<br />/OE connect to CHR /RD<br /><br />*On the NES cart edge cut the trace connecting CIRAM /CE and CHR /A13 and tie CIRAM /CE to Vcc. CHR /A13 should be left floating.<br /><br />*CIRAM A10 tie to Vcc or GND.  DO NOT leave it floating.  Alternatively you could use a trick if your board has H/V solder jumpers you can just close one of them, doesn't matter, just makes it cleaner with your board.  The ONLY requirement is that it's not floating.<br /><br />Keep in mind this has nothing connect to a mapper of any kind. And mirroring is fixed to 4-screen.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">BTW, don't the palettes get in the way since the RAM chip would be active when $3F00-$3FFF is accessed? Or does the fact that palette RAM is internal to the CPU make the external data not matter?</div><br />So I was thinking about this too.  If I understand it correctly it won't matter.  The address bus and control signals should be vaild when reading and writing to the palettes.  So what'll actually happen is you'll store the palettes internally in the PPU and on the cart, and you'll also read from both of them.  Since they should both agree after<strong> intializing </strong>them it's really a non-issue, they shouldn't conflict or cause issues.</div>

					
						<div class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />If you're gonna play the Game Boy, you gotta learn to play it right.  -Kenny Rogers</div>
