					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">infiniteneslives wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Alternatively you could use a trick if your board has H/V solder jumpers you can just close one of them, doesn't matter, just makes it cleaner with your board.</div><br />I was thinking about adding a few of switches so that the board could still be used for regular H/V mirroring, so it would be possible to temporarily revert the board to its original state.</div><br />Yes but keep in mind you'll need ~3 switches.  for VRAM /CE, CIRAM /CE, and mirroring.  My shortcut doesn't actually implement H/V mirroring, it's just a trick to get a valid logic level to CIRAM A10 to keep it from floating.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Yeah, this is meant for simpler mappers that only affect the PRG. I imagine that 4 screen mirroring would be hard with a single RAM chip on the MMC3, for example.</div><br />Yeah it would be a fair amount of discrete logic to do on a original MMC3 board.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I'm pretty sure the PPU doesn't lower /WR during palette writes. Otherwise, palette writes would corrupt the nametable, as $3xxx is usually a mirror of $2xxx.</div><br />I hope that this is also the case when external memory is used instead of CIRAM. On the other hand, since 8KB of RAM will be mapped at $2000-$3FFF, $3xxx will not be a mirror.</div><br />Oh yeah you got me, even though you'd now have specific memory mapped here and not a mirror, the same logic applies.  I guess it must not assert CHR /RD either otherwise it'd conflict for reads.  So long story short, it's a non-issue.<br /><br />EDIT:<s>But, on that note...  I always questioned those mirrors at PPU $3000-3FFF and where/how they are mirrored to exactly.  You&#39;re suggesting $2000-2FFF Tepples, but why?  The $3xxx would suggest PPU A14 is high, A13 is low, and A12 is high &#40;binary 101 = decimal 3&#41;.  So the mirroring exists since PPU A14 is only internal.  Externally A13 low and A12 high is only seen at the cart which would be $1xxx.  So in reality pattern table 1 is always mirrored against the palettes and this conflict is avoided by CHR /RD and CHR /WR not being asserted when PPU A14 is high I would imagine.  However if that were the case the mirrors wouldn&#39;t exist at all and $3xxx would all be a memory void aside from palettes, so if the $3xxx mirrors exist, CHR /WR /RD would only be kept from being asserted when the palettes are addressed.</s></div>

					
