						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">tokumaru wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">infiniteneslives wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I'll just stop making up stuff and quit while I'm behind <img src="./images/smilies/icon_wink.gif" alt=";)" title="Wink" /></div><br />For what it's worth, you did help a lot! =)</div><br /><br />Well I'm glad to see my weekly inability to remember binary conversions and the consequential rant of ridiculousness wasn't all a waste.  So I'll continue to ask potentially embarrasing questions because it seems we're both confused on this one:<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">lidnariq wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">An awfully wasteful, but potentially interesting application, would be to just connect PPU A12 → CHR RAM A14, leaving RAM always enabled. The nametables will exactly follow the chr-ram slices in $0xxx but will be entirely disjoint memory, and you're unlikely to map the same section of CHR-RAM to the same slice so should remain 4-screen mirroring.</div><br />Like tokuraru I don't get what this buys you.  So the RAM has A12 and A14 tied together, but how does that appear any differently than tieing A14 to gnd/vcc?   You effectively made 32KB work as 16KB which is what we already had.  The only thing different is how things are arranged in the SRAM, as far as I can tell it's all going to look the same to the PPU.<br /><br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">I just though of something else: since $3000-$3F00 will not be mirrors anymore, could I use that as an extra 3840 bytes of RAM accessible through the PPU bus when the PPU is not rendering? Yeah, I know, access is very restricted and probably no emulator will accept that configuration, but I just can't help thinking what use I could give to those bytes...</div><br />Yeah I'd think you should be able to use it no problem in that manner.  I suppose that might help out a bit if you're trying to keep yourself from using WRAM huh?  Basically $3000-3F00 just become cumbersome scratch pad, or a good place for save storage if battery backed etc.  EDIT: oh and if you released a game making use of that space I'm sure some people would be motivated enough to configure an emulator to support.</div>

					
